# gen130 (L20-deep): ROBUSTNESS by self-perturbation. Composes gen129's single
# ablation into a SWEEP — remove EACH ground fact in turn, re-derive, restore —
# to discover whether the last conclusion is FRAGILE (one load-bearing fact) or
# ROBUST (no single point of failure). This is knowledge a proof trace cannot
# give: a proof shows one derivation; ablation reveals whether others exist.

# Guard: nothing concluded yet.
> how robust is that conclusion?
< Ask me whether something holds first — then I can stress-test it.

# A purely DERIVED conclusion: mortal(socrates) hangs on the single fact
# man(socrates) through the rule. The sweep finds that one critical belief.
> socrates is a man
< Learned: man(socrates).
> every man is a mortal
< Learned rule: mortal(X) :- man(X).
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.
> how robust is that conclusion?
< My conclusion that socrates is a mortal is fragile: it rests entirely on one fact — man(socrates). Forget that and it falls.
# The sweep is non-destructive — every probe restored what it removed.
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.

# REDUNDANT support: plato is a mortal both directly AND via the rule, so no
# single fact is load-bearing — the conclusion is robust to any one loss.
> plato is a man
< Learned: man(plato).
> plato is a mortal
< Learned: mortal(plato).
> is plato a mortal?
< Yes.
> is your conclusion fragile?
< My conclusion that plato is a mortal is robust — there's no single fact I could forget that would overturn it.
